# Sparse Fast Fourier Transform Is All You Need

[![Affiliation](https://img.shields.io/badge/Affiliation-SCUPI-burgundy.svg)](https://scupi.scu.edu.cn/)
[![Course](https://img.shields.io/badge/Course-ECE--Analysis-blue.svg)](https://scupi.scu.edu.cn/)
[![Instructor](https://img.shields.io/badge/Instructor-Prof.%20Hao%20Qin-green.svg)](https://scupi.scu.edu.cn/)

This repository contains the official implementation and research paper for the **ECE Analysis** course project at **Sichuan University-Pittsburgh Institute (SCUPI)**. Under the guidance of **Prof. Hao Qin**, this project investigates the mechanics, history, and efficiency of the Sparse Fast Fourier Transform (SFFT) compared to traditional FFT methods.

## ðŸ“– Abstract

The Sparse Fast Fourier Transform (SFFT) is an advanced numerical algorithm designed to analyze signals with frequency-domain sparsity more efficiently than the traditional $O(N \log N)$ Fast Fourier Transform (FFT). [cite_start]This study involves a detailed mathematical analysis of SFFT mechanismsâ€”including hashing, filtering, and frequency recovery[cite: 386]. [cite_start]Our research demonstrates that SFFT offers a significant decline in computational complexity for large, sparse datasets without compromising accuracy, making it ideal for applications in medical imaging and wireless communication[cite: 381, 403].

## âœ¨ Key Research Contributions

- [cite_start]**Mathematical Decomposition**: In-depth analysis of randomized sub-linear time algorithms and their evolution from MIT and Michigan groups[cite: 387, 388].
- [cite_start]**Deterministic SFT Analysis**: Evaluation of deterministic methods that guarantee correctness, moving beyond the inherent failure probabilities of randomized methods[cite: 389, 391].
- [cite_start]**Structured Sparsity Optimization**: Exploration of **Block/Cluster Sparsity** (contiguous blocks) and **Polynomially Generated Sparsity** (algebraic structures)[cite: 403, 404].
- **Complexity Comparison**:
  - [cite_start]**Unstructured Deterministic**: $O(n^2 \log^{O(1)} N)$[cite: 395].
  - [cite_start]**Prony-based Methods**: $O(n^3)$ for $n$-sparse signals[cite: 398].
  - **Proposed Structured SFT**: Achieves faster recovery by exploiting the algebraic structure of the frequency support.

## ðŸš€ Performance Insights

[cite_start]Our findings indicate that for structured frequency supports, leveraging the structural prior dramatically reduces sampling and computational burdens[cite: 405].

| Feature         | Randomized SFFT                                | Deterministic SFFT                                      |
| :-------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Runtime**     | [cite_start]$O(n \log^{c} N)$ [cite: 389]      | [cite_start]$O(n^2 \log^{O(1)} N)$ [cite: 395]          |
| **Reliability** | [cite_start]Probability of failure [cite: 389] | [cite_start]Absolute reliability [cite: 389, 391]       |
| **Best Case**   | General sparse signals                         | [cite_start]Structured (Block/Poly) signals [cite: 404] |

## ðŸ›  Project Structure

- `/docs`: Contains the full research paper: _Sparse Fast Fourier Transform Is All You Need_.
- `/src`: Implementation of SFFT algorithms (Hashing, Bucket Sorting, and Frequency Estimation).
- `/experiments`: Reproducibility scripts for robustness testing and hashing collision analysis.

## ðŸ”§ Installation & Usage

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone [https://github.com/your-username/SFFT-ECE-Analysis.git](https://github.com/your-username/SFFT-ECE-Analysis.git)

# Navigate to the project directory
cd SFFT-ECE-Analysis

# Run the simulation
# Use --sparsity for n and --size for N
python main.py --sparsity 10 --size 1024
```
